title: Activation cross-sections of deuteron induced reactions on natGd up to 50 MeV

x4freetext: Activation cross-sections of deuteron induced
reactions on natGd up to 50 MeV

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Applied Radiation and Isotopes, Vol.83, p.25 (2014)

x4codes.hlp: Catholic Univ. of Louvain, Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium

x4freetext: Natural gadolinium foil, thickness: 83.9 microns
A stack containing
natural Gd foils as target, Al foils as
monitor foils and Sc foils as energy degraders and
other target material was irradiated with a deuteron
beam of 50 MeV, 120nA for 30 minutes at BLGLVN.
A stack containing natural Gd foils as target, Al and
Ti foils as monitor foils was irradiated with deuteron
beam of 21 MeV, 60nA for 110 minutes at BLGVUB. Gamma
spectra were measured non-destructively in 3 and 2
series respectively for the 50 and 21 MeV irradiations.

x4codes.shortRef: Rept: Nuclear Data Services (Doc. series of NDS), No.1211 (2001)
Jour: Nucl. Instrum. Methods in Physics Res., Sect.B, Vol.174, p.235 (2001)

x4freetext: The uncertainty on the median energy in the
foils includes the cumulative effects of uncertainty of
incident beam energy, uncertainty of stopping power of
each foil due to thickness variation and straggling
effects.
The uncertainty on the cross section values
are estimated in the standard way following the
recommendations of the ISO-guide as the square root of
the quadratic summation of the independently
contributing parameters. Uncertainty of time parameters
is not included.
surface density of target nuclei        (1%)
incident charged particle flux          (7%)
beam loss correction                  (1.5%)
detector efficiency           (5-7%)
statistical and peak fitting (1-20%)
Fitted excitation functions were used for
determination of integral physical yields.
Ts. 002 and 003 deleted. Duplication of
VS. SF4: -G added in subentries 010-011.
SF4: M+ deleted in 004.
Data in subent 006 and 008 were corrected.
Measured after complete decay of two isomeric states.
Data were taken from Table4 of the article.
VS. SF4: M+ deleted c.f. Memo CP-D/1023.
